{
	"visualizations": {
		"viz_tkz0p3Qf": {
			"type": "splunk.markdown",
			"options": {
				"markdown": "## Configuration\n\n**Cribl Stream**:\n1. Export key bundle from Cribl Stream by going to Group Settings -> Security -> Encryption Keys and clicking \"Get Key Bundle\"\n\n2. Repeat for each Worker Group that is sending encrypted data to Splunk\n\n**Cribl Decrypt Add-On for Splunk**:\n1. Go to the Key Management page in the Cribl Decrypt App and upload the key bundle. User will need *admin_all_objects* capability to upload the key bundle (default for *admin* role).\n\n2. Refreshing the page will show the uploaded keys in the list. Keys are stored in Splunk Secret Storage.\n\n3. To delete a key, enter the Key ID in the \"Delete a key\" sections field and click Delete.\n\n## Usage\n\nIn any search page, use the *cribldecrypt* command to decrypt data encrypted with Cribl Stream. Users will need to have the *list_storage_passwords* capability to access the keys (default for *admin* role).\n\nThe command has no options - it will decrypt any data encrypted by Cribl Stream for which keys have been uploaded, including `_raw` and fields in the event.\n\n`index=<index_name> | cribldecrypt`\n\nNote: Since this command requires access to the Search Head's REST interface, it is technically a [dataset processing command](https://docs.splunk.com/Splexicon:Datasetprocessingcommand), which means that it should appear as late as possible in the search string."
			}
		}
	},
	"dataSources": {},
	"defaults": {
		"dataSources": {
			"ds.search": {
				"options": {
					"queryParameters": {
						"latest": "$global_time.latest$",
						"earliest": "$global_time.earliest$"
					}
				}
			}
		}
	},
	"inputs": {},
	"layout": {
		"type": "absolute",
